{"title_page": "Anwar Yusuf Turani", "text_new": "{{Short description|American Uyghur nationalist}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anwar Yusuf Turani<br/>{{lang|ug|\u0626\u06d5\u0646\u06cb\u06d5\u0631 \u064a\u06c8\u0633\u06c8\u067e \u062a\u06c7\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649}}<br/>\u0410\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440 \u0419\u0443\u0441\u0443\u0444 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\n| image              = Anwar Yusuf at National Press Club.jpg\n| caption            = Anwar Yusuf Turani speaking at the [[National Press Club (USA)|National Press Club]] in Washington D.C. on November 22, 2004.\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1962|08|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Artux]], [[Xinjiang]], [[China]]\n| children           = 4\n| occupation         = Political activist, educator, musician\n| residence          = Virginia, United States\n| movement           = [[East Turkistan independence movement]]\n| organization       = East Turkistan National Freedom Center (ETNFC)\n| title              = President of the East Turkistan Government in Exile (2019-Present)\nFormer Prime Minister of the East Turkistan Government in Exile (2004-2019)<ref>http://eastturkistangovernmentinexile.us/government_officials.html</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7dBPjNkMek&t=5973s</ref><ref>https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Voice_of_America_Report_on_Chinese_Opposition_of_ETGIE.ogg</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Anwar Yusuf Turani''' ({{lang-ug|\u0626\u06d5\u0646\u06cb\u06d5\u0631 \u064a\u06c8\u0633\u06c8\u067e \u062a\u06c7\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649|ucy=\u0410\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440 \u0419\u0443\u0441\u0443\u0444 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438}}) is an ethnic [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] [[East Turkestan independence movement|nationalist]]. Born into a family branded [[counter-revolutionary]], Uyghur nationalist and separatist by the [[Government of China|Chinese government]], Turani was raised in a labor camp where he faced economic hardship and political oppression. Turani attended [[Kashgar University|Kashgar Teacher's College]] and graduated from the Department of Physics in July 1983. Turani came to the United States on August 12, 1988 and became the first Uyghur political asylee. In 1995, Turani established the East Turkistan National Freedom Center (ETNFC), a non-profit human rights organization based in Washington DC. He is the first person to start the [[East Turkistan independence movement]] in the United States. In 2004, Turani and other prominent Uyghur independence activists set up the East Turkistan Government in Exile (ETGIE) and Turani was elected as the first Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bovingdon |first1=Gardner |title=The Uyghurs: Strangers in Their Own Land |year=2010 |publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York |pages=150\u2013151 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=2 |accessdate=2012-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020225351/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |archive-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n===East Turkistan National Freedom Center===\nAs the president of the East Turkistan National Freedom Center, Turani organized demonstrations, conferences and cultural events, concerning the situation of East Turkistan. He also met with many international dignitaries, including U.S. President Bill Clinton, Tibetan Leader Dalai Lama and Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian, in an attempt to gain their support in ending the occupation of his nation.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D7-23Rm_qTc Anwar Yusuf Turani: An Uyghur-Muslim Challenge to Chinese Authority in East Turkistan]</ref> In April 1996, Turani met with [[Tenzin Gyatso]], the 14th Dalai Lama, forging an alliance between East Turkistan and [[Tibet]] against the Chinese government.  Later that month, Turani and representatives of occupied Tibet and Inner Mongolia organized an Independence Walk from the Chinese embassy in Washington D.C. to the [[United Nations]] in New York City. At the end of the two-week walk, Turani spoke in front of the United Nations headquarters, addressing the Chinese human rights violations in East Turkistan since 1949.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qZgH_Df7O64 UN Speech by Anwar Yusuf Turani (Part 1), April 25, 1996]</ref>\n\nIn June 1997, along with the support of the [[Tibetan Independence Movement]], Turani cut one of the five stars from the national flag of China in front of the United Nations. Turani removed the star as a symbolic gesture of his nation's yearning to liberate themselves from Chinese occupation.<ref>{{cite web|title=March for Tibet's Independence|url=http://www.rangzen.com/archive/97/march/days/061497.htm|publisher=International Tibet Independence Movement|year=1997}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1998, Turani visited Taiwan at the invitation of the [[World Federation of Taiwanese Associations]], along with [[Erkin Alptekin]]; Professor [[Thubten Jigme Norbu]], elder brother of  the Dalai Lama; Tashi Jamyangling, former Home Secretary of the Tibetan Government in exile; and Johnar Bache, Vice Chairman of the Southern Mongolian People's Party.  They met [[Taiwan independence]] activists and the pro Taiwan independence [[Democratic Progressive Party]] members [[Liu Sung-pan]], the President of Taiwan's Legislative Yuan; [[Chen Shui-bian]], former president of Taiwan; and [[Frank Hsieh]], the Mayor of Kaosiung.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raman |first=B. |title=US & Terrorism in Xinjiang |url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/paper409 |publisher=South Asia Analysis Group |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |date=2002-07-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106031937/http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/paper409 |archivedate=2014-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 1999, Turani met with [[US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in order to persuade him to back the [[East Turkistan independence movement]].<ref name=\"starr-382\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page=382 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA382 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> Turani told Clinton that his nation is in favor of waging a [[war of independence]] against China;<ref name=\"gladney-245\">{{cite book |title=Dislocating China: Muslims, Minorities, and Other Subaltern Subjects. |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |year=2004 |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |location=Chicago |isbn=0-226-29775-6 |page=245 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mzxSNM3_vCEC&pg=PA245 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref name=\"starr-387\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page=387 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA387 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref>.  Turani claimed to had been funded by wealthy Uyghurs in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"starr-388\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page= |pages=388&ndash;389 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA388 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2001 Turani received a letter from the [[United States Department of State]] on behalf of President [[George W. Bush]] in response to Turani's initial letter concerning the Chinese occupation of East Turkistan.  In this letter, the U.S. government expressed its willingness to protect the \"fundamental human rights -- the rights to freedom of association, assembly, religion, belief, conscience, and expression -- of Uyghurs and others living in China.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Yusuf|first=Anwar|title=Letter from State Department|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=139264989488298&set=pb.100002143949228.-2207520000.1357532238&type=3&theater|date=2001-07-20}}</ref>\n\n===East Turkistan Government in Exile===\nOn September 14, 2004, Anwar Yusuf Turani proclaimed the creation of the \"East Turkistan [[Government in Exile]]\" in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite press release |title=The Formation of the East Turkistan Government in Exile |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2004-09-13 |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-formation-of-the-east-turkistan-government-in-exile-72189487.html |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> and was elected Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite book |title=The ETIM: China's Islamic militants and the global terrorist threat |last1=Reed |first1=J. Todd |authorlink= |last2=Raschke |first2=Diana |year=2010 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=978-0-313-36540-9 |page=34 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5I2b_hrJO8sC&pg=PA34 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The New Silk Road Diplomacy: China's Central Asian Foreign Policy since the Cold War |last=Karrar |first=Hasan Haider |authorlink= |year=2009 |publisher=[[UBC Press]] |location=Vancouver, British Columbia |isbn=978-0-7748-1692-2 |page=116 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VqsXa70agc0C&pg=PT116 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> China's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] spokesperson Kong Quan publicly registered his displeasure, referencing such groups' [[Terrorism in the People's Republic of China|terrorism in the Xinjiang region]].;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-a-2004-09-21-3-China-67507892.html |title=China Protests Establishment of Uighur Government-in-Exile in Washington |author= |date=2004-09-21 |work=[[Voice of America]] |publisher= |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2004/09/22/2004092261001.html |title=China Protests Establishment of Uighur Government-in-Exile in Washington |author= |date=2004-09-22 |work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]] |publisher= |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> In November, the United States Government declared that it \"does not recognize any East Turkestan government-in-exile, nor do we provide support for any such entity\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2004/38594.htm|title=China - No Recognition of Any East Turkestanmore  Government in Exile (Taken Question)|date=November 22, 2004|publisher=United States Department of State}}</ref> In 2006, Turani was impeached by the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile's Parliament for violating its Constitution and was permanently banned from being a member of the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile and its Parliament after he associated himself with the jihadist [[Turkistan Islamic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Concerning Persons Undermining the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile |url=https://east-turkistan.net/statement-concerning-persons-undermining-the-east-turkistan-government-in-exile/ |website=East Turkistan Government in Exile |publisher=ETGE High Commission |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Turani criticized the People's Republic of China for imprisoning Uyghur imam [[Huseyincan Celil]]. Turani compared Celil's arrest to that of [[Rebiya Kadeer]] and theorized that the PRC wanted to use Celil as leverage against [[Canada]], where Celil held citizenship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=2 |accessdate=2012-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020225351/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |archive-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=2 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=3 |accessdate=2012-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107192552/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=2 |archive-date=January 7, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, Turani has been addressing the primary issues that the people of East Turkistan are facing both in their homeland and abroad. Turani regularly{{vague|date=August 2018}} issues press releases in the native Uyghur language to educate the Uyghur people of their history and situation, and to show them a path toward their independence.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SanVbmLhMxM&context=C31b033aUDOEgsToPDskIkUgup3Nb15W4dARvbWFrL \u2018\u2019Weten Dawasi\u201d,  STJSH' ning \"Weten Dawasi\" Heqqidiki Bayanati (1/3-Bolum), April 22, 2011, January 5, 2012]</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Rebiya Kadeer accused the Chinese government of intentionally cultivating multiple Uyghur governments in exile in order to divide the Uyghur people. She believes that [[independence movement]]s have less support in the [[international community]] and considers pressing for increased [[self-determination]] within a unified China to be a better strategic approach.<ref name=\"2011 Kadeer\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 27, 2011 |title= Interview: 'I Can't Say The Struggle Will Always Be Peaceful,' Says Uyghur Advocate Kadeer |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/interview_rebiya_kadeer_uyghurs_china/2322376.html |newspaper=Radio Free Europe Radio Liberty |location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Uyghur Americans]]\n*[[Xinjiang re-education camps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Peterson |first1=Kristian |year=2006 |title=Usurping the Nation: Cyber-leadership in the Uighur Nationalist Movement |journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=64 |url=https://washington.academia.edu/KristianPetersen/Papers/113612/Usurping_the_Nation_Cyber-leadership_in_the_Uighur_Nationalist_Movement |doi=10.1080/13602000600738681}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anwar Yusuf Turani}}\n*[http://www.eastturkistangovernmentinexile.us/anwar_biography.html About Anwar Yusuf Turani] &ndash; East Turkistan government-in-exile website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turani, Anwar Yusuf}}\n[[Category:Uyghur activists]]\n[[Category:Uyghur nationalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n[[Category:East Turkestan independence movement]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American Uyghur nationalist}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Anwar Yusuf Turani<br/>{{lang|ug|\u0626\u06d5\u0646\u06cb\u06d5\u0631 \u064a\u06c8\u0633\u06c8\u067e \u062a\u06c7\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649}}<br/>\u0410\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440 \u0419\u0443\u0441\u0443\u0444 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\n| image              = Anwar Yusuf at National Press Club.jpg\n| caption            = Anwar Yusuf Turani speaking at the [[National Press Club (USA)|National Press Club]] in Washington D.C. on November 22, 2004.\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1962|08|03|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Artux]], [[Xinjiang]], [[China]]\n| children           = 4\n| occupation         = Political activist, educator, musician\n| residence          = Virginia, United States\n| movement           = [[East Turkistan independence movement]]\n| organization       = East Turkistan National Freedom Center (ETNFC)\n| title              = Former Prime Minister of the East Turkistan Government in Exile (2004-2006)\n}}\n\n'''Anwar Yusuf Turani''' ({{lang-ug|\u0626\u06d5\u0646\u06cb\u06d5\u0631 \u064a\u06c8\u0633\u06c8\u067e \u062a\u06c7\u0631\u0627\u0646\u0649|ucy=\u0410\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440 \u0419\u0443\u0441\u0443\u0444 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438}}) is an ethnic [[Uyghurs|Uyghur]] [[East Turkestan independence movement|nationalist]]. Born into a family branded [[counter-revolutionary]], Uyghur nationalist and separatist by the [[Government of China|Chinese government]], Turani was raised in a labor camp where he faced economic hardship and political oppression. Turani attended [[Kashgar University|Kashgar Teacher's College]] and graduated from the Department of Physics in July 1983. Turani came to the United States on August 12, 1988 and became the first Uyghur political asylee. In 1995, Turani established the East Turkistan National Freedom Center (ETNFC), a non-profit human rights organization based in Washington DC. He is the first person to start the [[East Turkistan independence movement]] in the United States. In 2004, Turani and other prominent Uyghur independence activists set up the East Turkistan Government in Exile (ETGIE) and Turani was elected as the first Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bovingdon |first1=Gardner |title=The Uyghurs: Strangers in Their Own Land |year=2010 |publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York |pages=150\u2013151 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=2 |accessdate=2012-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020225351/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |archive-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n===East Turkistan National Freedom Center===\nAs the president of the East Turkistan National Freedom Center, Turani organized demonstrations, conferences and cultural events, concerning the situation of East Turkistan. He also met with many international dignitaries, including U.S. President Bill Clinton, Tibetan Leader Dalai Lama and Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian, in an attempt to gain their support in ending the occupation of his nation.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D7-23Rm_qTc Anwar Yusuf Turani: An Uyghur-Muslim Challenge to Chinese Authority in East Turkistan]</ref> In April 1996, Turani met with [[Tenzin Gyatso]], the 14th Dalai Lama, forging an alliance between East Turkistan and [[Tibet]] against the Chinese government.  Later that month, Turani and representatives of occupied Tibet and Inner Mongolia organized an Independence Walk from the Chinese embassy in Washington D.C. to the [[United Nations]] in New York City. At the end of the two-week walk, Turani spoke in front of the United Nations headquarters, addressing the Chinese human rights violations in East Turkistan since 1949.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qZgH_Df7O64 UN Speech by Anwar Yusuf Turani (Part 1), April 25, 1996]</ref>\n\nIn June 1997, along with the support of the [[Tibetan Independence Movement]], Turani cut one of the five stars from the national flag of China in front of the United Nations. Turani removed the star as a symbolic gesture of his nation's yearning to liberate themselves from Chinese occupation.<ref>{{cite web|title=March for Tibet's Independence|url=http://www.rangzen.com/archive/97/march/days/061497.htm|publisher=International Tibet Independence Movement|year=1997}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1998, Turani visited Taiwan at the invitation of the [[World Federation of Taiwanese Associations]], along with [[Erkin Alptekin]]; Professor [[Thubten Jigme Norbu]], elder brother of  the Dalai Lama; Tashi Jamyangling, former Home Secretary of the Tibetan Government in exile; and Johnar Bache, Vice Chairman of the Southern Mongolian People's Party.  They met [[Taiwan independence]] activists and the pro Taiwan independence [[Democratic Progressive Party]] members [[Liu Sung-pan]], the President of Taiwan's Legislative Yuan; [[Chen Shui-bian]], former president of Taiwan; and [[Frank Hsieh]], the Mayor of Kaosiung.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raman |first=B. |title=US & Terrorism in Xinjiang |url=http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/paper409 |publisher=South Asia Analysis Group |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |date=2002-07-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106031937/http://www.southasiaanalysis.org/paper409 |archivedate=2014-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 1999, Turani met with [[US President]] [[Bill Clinton]] in order to persuade him to back the [[East Turkistan independence movement]].<ref name=\"starr-382\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page=382 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA382 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> Turani told Clinton that his nation is in favor of waging a [[war of independence]] against China;<ref name=\"gladney-245\">{{cite book |title=Dislocating China: Muslims, Minorities, and Other Subaltern Subjects. |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |year=2004 |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |location=Chicago |isbn=0-226-29775-6 |page=245 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mzxSNM3_vCEC&pg=PA245 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref name=\"starr-387\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page=387 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA387 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref>.  Turani claimed to had been funded by wealthy Uyghurs in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"starr-388\">{{cite book |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |last=Gladney |first=Dru C. |authorlink=Dru C. Gladney |editor-last=Starr |editor-first=S. Frederick |editor-link=S. Frederick Starr |year=2004 |publisher=[[Central Asia-Caucasus Institute]] |location=Armonk, New York |isbn=0-7656-1317-4 |page= |pages=388&ndash;389 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&pg=PA388 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn July 20, 2001 Turani received a letter from the [[United States Department of State]] on behalf of President [[George W. Bush]] in response to Turani's initial letter concerning the Chinese occupation of East Turkistan.  In this letter, the U.S. government expressed its willingness to protect the \"fundamental human rights -- the rights to freedom of association, assembly, religion, belief, conscience, and expression -- of Uyghurs and others living in China.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Yusuf|first=Anwar|title=Letter from State Department|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=139264989488298&set=pb.100002143949228.-2207520000.1357532238&type=3&theater|date=2001-07-20}}</ref>\n\n===East Turkistan Government in Exile===\nOn September 14, 2004, Anwar Yusuf Turani proclaimed the creation of the \"East Turkistan [[Government in Exile]]\" in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite press release |title=The Formation of the East Turkistan Government in Exile |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |date=2004-09-13 |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-formation-of-the-east-turkistan-government-in-exile-72189487.html |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> and was elected Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite book |title=The ETIM: China's Islamic militants and the global terrorist threat |last1=Reed |first1=J. Todd |authorlink= |last2=Raschke |first2=Diana |year=2010 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |location=Santa Barbara, California |isbn=978-0-313-36540-9 |page=34 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5I2b_hrJO8sC&pg=PA34 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The New Silk Road Diplomacy: China's Central Asian Foreign Policy since the Cold War |last=Karrar |first=Hasan Haider |authorlink= |year=2009 |publisher=[[UBC Press]] |location=Vancouver, British Columbia |isbn=978-0-7748-1692-2 |page=116 |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VqsXa70agc0C&pg=PT116 |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> China's [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] spokesperson Kong Quan publicly registered his displeasure, referencing such groups' [[Terrorism in the People's Republic of China|terrorism in the Xinjiang region]].;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-a-2004-09-21-3-China-67507892.html |title=China Protests Establishment of Uighur Government-in-Exile in Washington |author= |date=2004-09-21 |work=[[Voice of America]] |publisher= |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2004/09/22/2004092261001.html |title=China Protests Establishment of Uighur Government-in-Exile in Washington |author= |date=2004-09-22 |work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]] |publisher= |accessdate=2011-12-21}}</ref> In November, the United States Government declared that it \"does not recognize any East Turkestan government-in-exile, nor do we provide support for any such entity\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2004/38594.htm|title=China - No Recognition of Any East Turkestanmore  Government in Exile (Taken Question)|date=November 22, 2004|publisher=United States Department of State}}</ref> In 2006, Turani was impeached by the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile's Parliament for violating its Constitution and was permanently banned from being a member of the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile and its Parliament after he associated himself with the jihadist [[Turkistan Islamic Party]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Concerning Persons Undermining the East Turkistan Government-in-Exile |url=https://east-turkistan.net/statement-concerning-persons-undermining-the-east-turkistan-government-in-exile/ |website=East Turkistan Government in Exile |publisher=ETGE High Commission |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Turani criticized the People's Republic of China for imprisoning Uyghur imam [[Huseyincan Celil]]. Turani compared Celil's arrest to that of [[Rebiya Kadeer]] and theorized that the PRC wanted to use Celil as leverage against [[Canada]], where Celil held citizenship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=2 |accessdate=2012-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020225351/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=1 |archive-date=October 20, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=2 |title=The Uyghur pawn |first=Kevin |last=Steel |date=2007-05-21 |work=[[Western Standard]] |page=3 |accessdate=2012-01-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107192552/http://www.westernstandard.ca/website/article.php?id=2542&start=2 |archive-date=January 7, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince 2007, Turani has been addressing the primary issues that the people of East Turkistan are facing both in their homeland and abroad. Turani regularly{{vague|date=August 2018}} issues press releases in the native Uyghur language to educate the Uyghur people of their history and situation, and to show them a path toward their independence.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SanVbmLhMxM&context=C31b033aUDOEgsToPDskIkUgup3Nb15W4dARvbWFrL \u2018\u2019Weten Dawasi\u201d,  STJSH' ning \"Weten Dawasi\" Heqqidiki Bayanati (1/3-Bolum), April 22, 2011, January 5, 2012]</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Rebiya Kadeer accused the Chinese government of intentionally cultivating multiple Uyghur governments in exile in order to divide the Uyghur people. She believes that [[independence movement]]s have less support in the [[international community]] and considers pressing for increased [[self-determination]] within a unified China to be a better strategic approach.<ref name=\"2011 Kadeer\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=February 27, 2011 |title= Interview: 'I Can't Say The Struggle Will Always Be Peaceful,' Says Uyghur Advocate Kadeer |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/interview_rebiya_kadeer_uyghurs_china/2322376.html |newspaper=Radio Free Europe Radio Liberty |location= |access-date= }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Uyghur Americans]]\n*[[Xinjiang re-education camps]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Peterson |first1=Kristian |year=2006 |title=Usurping the Nation: Cyber-leadership in the Uighur Nationalist Movement |journal=Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs |volume=26 |issue=1 |pages=64 |url=https://washington.academia.edu/KristianPetersen/Papers/113612/Usurping_the_Nation_Cyber-leadership_in_the_Uighur_Nationalist_Movement |doi=10.1080/13602000600738681}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Anwar Yusuf Turani}}\n*[http://www.eastturkistangovernmentinexile.us/anwar_biography.html About Anwar Yusuf Turani] &ndash; East Turkistan government-in-exile website\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turani, Anwar Yusuf}}\n[[Category:Uyghur activists]]\n[[Category:Uyghur nationalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n[[Category:East Turkestan independence movement]]\n", "name_user": "Humanrights246", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated current title including references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anwar_Yusuf_Turani"}
