.thechieftains.com The Chieftains Official website]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2yOfdOBwP4 youtube.com, Jeff White, \"Run Little Rabbit Run\", March 24, 2016]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n{{Alison Krauss}}\n{{Patty Loveless}}\n{{Loretta Lynn}}\n{{Charley Pride}}\n{{The Chieftains}}\n{{commons category|The Chieftains}}\n{{Commons category|Alison Krauss}}\n{{Commons category|Loretta Lynn}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American mandolinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American bluegrass musicians]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Production sound mixers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Jeff White\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1957}}\n| birth_place   =  [[Syracuse, New York]] \n| genre = [[Bluegrass music|Bluegrass]], [[Country music|Country]], [[Folk music|Folk]]\n| origin = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], United States\n| occupation =  Singer, musician, songwriter, record producer, sound mixer\n| associated_acts  = [[Alison Krauss]], [[Vince Gill]], [[The Chieftans]], [[Lyle Lovett]], [[Tim O'Brien (musician)|Tim O'Brien]], [[The Travelin' McCourys]], [[Michael Cleveland]] and [[The Earls of Leicester (band)|The Earls Of Leicester]]\n| years_active = 1979\u2013present\n| background= solo_singer\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Guitar|Mandolin}}\n}}\n\n'''Jeff White''' is American [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] guitarist/mandolinist, songwriter, record producer and sound mixer. Jeff White has performed and produced albums with many artists including: [[Alison Krauss]], [[Vince Gill]], [[The Chieftans]], [[Lyle Lovett]], [[Tim O'Brien (musician)|Tim O'Brien]], [[The Travelin' McCourys]], [[Michael Cleveland]] and [[The Earls of Leicester (band)|The Earls Of Leicester]]. One of Jeff's key mentors is award-winning fiddler Michael Cleveland. Jeff and Michael have earned four [[International Bluegrass Music Awards]] for Instrumental Recorded Performance of the Year. Jeff produced several of Michael Cleveland's albums. Jeff has toured with banjo picking [[Earl Scruggs]] and [[Louise Scruggs]]. Jeff White has produced and released four solo albums: in 1996 ''The White Album'', in 1999 ''The Broken Road'', in 2013 ''Renegade Revelations'' and in 2016 ''Right Beside You''.<ref>[https://bluegrasstoday.com/tag/jeff-white/ bluegrasstoday.com, Jeff White]</ref><ref>[https://www.herald-dispatch.com/features_entertainment/vince-gill-returns-with-his-talented-guitarist-of-years/article_243bdc7d-79d4-5a72-a632-89da0e9a0105.html herald-dispatch.com, Vince Grill guitarist]</ref>\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|bgcolor = MistyRose|quote=Terrific musicianship, top-quality production, and astounding song selection \u2014 Right Beside You ought to be nominated for Recorded Event of 2016. Traditional bluegrass remains safe in these hands. Dick Bowden with Bluegrass Today.<ref>[https://bluegrasstoday.com/right-beside-you-jeff-white/ Dick Bowden with Bluegrass Today, May 2, 2016]</ref>}}\n\n==Biography==\nJeff White was born in 1967 in [[Syracuse, New York]], at 13 his family moved to [[North Manchester, Indiana]]. Jeff's first interest in bluegrass and country music came from seeing the [[Hee Haw]] television show that started in 1971. Jeff started to play guitar in high school and joined the high school bluegrass band The ''Suburban Grass''. The band played at schools, coffeehouses and then local bars. In college Jeff discovered his love for bluegrass from a dorm mate that played mandolin. Jeff's dorm mate introduced Jeff to [[Doc Watson]], a pioneer of bluegrass music. Jeff studied [[Dan Crary]], [[Norman Blake (American musician)|Norman Blake]], [[Don Reno]], [[Bill Monroe]], [[Lester Flatt]], [[Earl Scruggs]], [[Foggy Mountain Boys]] and [[The Stanley Brothers]]. After listing to and learning form the classics, Jeff studied the new bluegrass artists like [[Sam Bush]] and [[JD Crowe]]. The next band Jeff joined was The Johnsons. Jeff White and The Johnsons came in 1st place in the Best Bluegrass Band in America contest, put on by [[KFC]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] in 1979. Winning the contest earned them a free recording session in RCA's Nashville studio on [[Music row]]. Tom Collins, an album producer with Real Music City Records, helped them make two singles. In 1981 Jeff White and The Johnsons where named the Best New Bluegrass Band. The Johnsons Band was made up of: Don Johnson, Dan Anderson, Melody Johnson and Jeff White.<ref>Billboard, September 18, 1982, page 50</ref>  White departed the group and returned to Indiana to attend graduate school. But, Jeff returned to bluegrass and moved to [[Beanblossom, Indiana]], there he joined up with a new and upcoming bluegrass fiddler [[Alison Krauss]]. In 1987, Jeff join Alison Krauss band the [[Union Station (band)|Union Station]]. Union Station recorded two albums while he was a member: in 1989 ''Two Highways'' and in 1990  ''I've Got That Old Feeling''. A seaside resort in Japan wanted a bluegrass music band, so Jeff joined other bluegrass artists: [[Scott Vestal]], Jeff Autry, Dave Peters, and Gena Britt in 1991 and play for a year. Jeff moved to Nashville in 1992, he played bluegrass at the Station Inn with [[Tim O'Brien (musician)|Tim O'Brien]]. Jeff broke into professional music when [[Vince Gill]] took Jeff on the road with [[George Jones]] and [[Conway Twitty]]. Vince Gill had Jeff sing ''When I Call Your Name'' at the [[Grand Ole Opry]]. Vince Gill got Jeff a job playing with [[Lyle Lovett]]. Jeff's next job was playing with the traditional Irish band formed in Dublin [[The Chieftains]]. Looking to cross Celtic music with bluegrass and country, [[Paddy Moloney]] looked to Jeff to help with the new sound. Jeff toured, performed and helped produce the 2002 The Chieftains album ''[[Down the Old Plank Road: The Nashville Sessions]]'' and in 2003 ''[[Further Down the Old Plank Road]]''. Jeff's next project was working with bluegrass fiddle player [[Michael Cleveland]] on his albums. Jeff is also a songwriter and has written songs for The [[Del McCoury Band]], Alison Krauss, Dan Tyminski, Dale Ann Bradley, Stringdusters and Dan Tyminski. Jeff sometimes plays guitar with the Nashville bluegrass band [[The Travelin' McCourys]]. Jeff currently plays mandolin for [[The Earls of Leicester (band)|The Earls of Leicester]], a band that plays tribute to  Flatt and Scruggs. Jeff is married to country music [[fiddler]], guitarist, singer and songwriter, [[Laura Weber White]]. Jeff and Laura live in Nashville and were married on March 12, 2017.<ref>[https://www.oldtownschool.org/concerts/2019/03-08-2019-the-earls-of-leicester/ oldtownschool.org, The Earls of Leicester]</ref><ref>[http://lauraweberwhite.com/biography.html lauraweberwhite.com Laura Weber White Biography]</ref><ref>[http://www.jeffwhitebluegrass.com/bio.html Jeff White Bio]</ref><ref>[https://bluegrasstoday.com/laura-weber-cash-and-jeff-white-wed-in-goodlettsville-tn/ Laura Weber Cash and Jeff White Wed in Goodlettsville, TN, March 15, 2017 by Dick Bowden]</ref><ref>[https://www.mandolincafe.com/news/publish/mandolins_001243.shtml mandolincafe.com, 10 Questions for Laura Weber Cash, By Mandolin Cafe, August 3, 2010 ]</ref><ref>[https://airplaydirect.com/?p=2636 Jeff White Inks Artist Endorsement Deal With Airplay Direct, April 16, 2016]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\nJeff White's discography:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/638206-Jeff-White-2|title=Jeff Whites|website=Discogs|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n===Albums===\n'''Solo Albums'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! rowspan=\"