veland\n| Instrumental Recorded Performance of the Year, produced by Jeff White & Michael Cleveland\n|-\n\n| 2017\n| Earls of Leicester \n| style=\"text-align:center;| Earls of Leicester \n| 28th annual International Bluegrass Music Awards, Entertainer of the Year award<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/2017-bluegrass-awards-earls-of-leicester-named-entertainer-of-the-year-253441/ rollingstone.com, 2017 Bluegrass Awards: Earls of Leicester Named Entertainer of the Year, By Stephen L. Betts, September 29, 2017]</ref><ref>[https://earlsofleicester.net/about/ earlsofleicester.net, The Earls of Leicester office website]</ref>\n|-\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [[List of country musicians]]\n{{clear right}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.jeffwhitebluegrass.com}}\n* [http://www.thechieftains.com The Chieftains Official website]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o2yOfdOBwP4 youtube.com, Jeff White, \"Run Little Rabbit Run\", March 24, 2016]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n{{Alison Krauss}}\n{{Patty Loveless}}\n{{Loretta Lynn}}\n{{Charley Pride}}\n{{The Chieftains}}\n{{commons category|The Chieftains}}\n{{Commons category|Alison Krauss}}\n{{Commons category|Loretta Lynn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American mandolinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American bluegrass musicians]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Production sound mixers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_White_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Central Ontario Railway", "text_new": "{{Infobox rail | gauge={{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n|railroad_name= Central Ontario Railway\n|marks=COR\n|image=COR first train arrival.jpg\n|image_caption=A crowd gathers on the Central Ontario Railway platform in Bancroft to await the arrival of the first train on 2 November 1900.\n|logo_size=125\n|logo_filename=\n|system_map=\n|map_size=\n|map_caption= \n|old_gauge=\n|locale=[[Ontario]], Canada\n|start_year= 1879\n|end_year=1984\n|hq_city=\n|length={{convert|50.9|miles}}\n|predecessor_line  = Prince Edward County Railway\n|successor_line    = Canadian Northern Railway/ CN\n}}\n\nThe '''Central Ontario Railway''' ('''COR''') was a former [[railway]] that ran north from [[Trenton, Ontario]] to service a number of towns, mines and sawmills. The railway originally formed as the '''Prince Edward County Railway''' in 1879, running between [[Picton, Ontario|Picton]] and Trenton, where it connected with the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] that ran between [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]]. After being purchased by a group of investors and receiving a new charter to build northward, the railway renamed as the COR in 1882 and the company started building towards the gold fields at [[Madoc, Ontario|Eldorado]] and newly discovered iron fields in Coe Hill.\n\nOn reaching Coe Hill in 1884, the mine was found to have low grade ore, nearly bankrupting the company. Expansion continued to other mining areas around [[Bancroft, Ontario|Bancroft]], along with two wholly owned subsidiary lines, the '''Ontario, Belmont and Northern Railway''', later known as the '''Marmora Railway''', and the '''Bessemer and Barry's Bay Railway'''. The later was supposed to connect to the [[Ottawa, Arnprior and Parry Sound Railway]] (OA&PS) at [[Barry's Bay, Ontario|Barry's Bay]], but these plans were shelved. A new route to the OA&PS was selected to [[Whitney, Ontario|Whitney]], just outside [[Algonquin Provincial Park]]. Construction on this final portion reached [[Maynooth, Ontario|Maynooth]] in 1907 but was never completed, and the line ultimately ended in the now abandoned town of Wallace, about 25 kilometres south of Whitney.\n\nThe COR was taken over by [[William Mackenzie (railway entrepreneur)|Mackenzie]] and [[Donald Mann|Mann]] in 1910, along with the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway]] which was connected to the COR north of Bancroft in July 1910. Both lines were then merged into their [[Canadian Northern Railway]] (CNoR) in 1911. After CNoR was nationalized 1918, the lines became part of the [[Canadian National Railways]] (CN) system in 1923. CN operated the COR as the '''Maynooth Subdivision'''. Sections of the line north of Maynooth were lifted in 1965, and the entire rest of the line in 1985. All of the side branches had been abandoned much earlier, typically when the ore deposits dried up.\n\nMuch of the route of the COR has been re-purposed as a multi-use recreational [[rail trail]], which has a variety of names depending on its location, with the '''Hastings Heritage Trail''' being a prominent part.\n\n==History==\n\n===Prince Edward County Railway===\n[[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]] is a large peninsula on eastern [[Lake Ontario]]. It is roughly triangular in shape with its apex pointed to the east, and its connection to the mainland at the northwestern corner. It was first settled starting in 1784 by [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalists]] after the [[American Revolutionary War]], and depended largely on fishing and barley in its early days.\n\nThe [[Grand Trunk Railway]] (GTR) reached [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]] on its way to Toronto in 1855, opening new markets to the County. Local businessmen began considering a railway to collect produce from across the peninsula and connecting with the GTR at Trenton, on the north side of the land bridge with the mainland.{{sfn|Brown|2011}} The Prince Edward County Railway company (PECR) was formed in 1873{{efn|Sources disagree on the date, some suggesting that it was formed in 1879 and opened in 1880, while others give 1873 as the formation and 1879 as the opening date.}} and began construction due west out of Picton towards the western shore of the peninsula, then turning northward for Trenton. Due to financial constraints, the line finally completed in 1879 and opened for service in October.{{sfn|Brown|2011}} In 1976 a large branch was wyed off west of Picton to serve large quarries north of town, near Elmbrook.\n\n===Expansion to Coe Hill===\nThe opening of [[Central Ontario]] during the 19th Century was driven primarily by the discovery of a number of mineral deposits, notably gold and iron ore. As mines grew, principally in the area of [[Marmora, Ontario|Marmora]] and [[Madoc, Ontario|Madoc]], a race formed between a series of railways companies who wanted to serve these markets. Among the many claimants were the [[Victoria Railway]] (VicR) that ran through [[Lindsay, Ontario|Lindsay]], a combined rail and water route by the [[Cobourg and Peterborough Railway]] (C&P), and a potential extension of the [[Toronto and Nipissing Railway]]. None of these were well placed though, as they ran towards Toronto instead of east to the major markets and shipping routes. The only line that appeared to be well positioned was a proposed branch of the [[Grand Junction Railway (Ontario)|Grand Junction Railway]] (GJR) out of Belleville. Since the new mining areas were directly north of both Trenton and Belleville, the PERC was also in an ideal location as a starting point.\n\nWilliam Coe of [[Madoc, Ontario|Madoc]] found [[iron ore]] deposits outside Brinklow and began looking for ways to commercialize the find. He contacted [[George William McMullen]], a railway promoter in [[Chicago]] who had been born and raised in Picton. McMullen started looking for partners, and found [[Samuel Ritchey]], a businessman from [[Ohio]] who was looking for new ventures. Rickey, McMullen and McMullen's brother J.B. bought the PECR in 1880 to serve as the basis for a rapid expansion. In 1881 the group purchased 70,000 acres of land for the mines, and transferred the deeds to the company.{{sfn|Bray}} The group then petitioned the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario Legislature]] for the rights to rename the company and start construction northward, which was granted on 10 March 1882.{{sfn|Walker|2013}} The land deeds were transferred to the newly formed Coe Hill Mining Company, and the railway was renamed the Central Ontario Railway.{{sfn|Bray}}\n\nThe route was selected to take the line through several other mining areas, including Marmora, Deloro and Malone, before reaching Eldorado. The line reached Marmora in 1883 and the newly formed [[Wollaston, Ontario|Coe Hill]] in 1884.{{efn|Most sources agree this took place in 1884, either directly or by saying \"two years later\" after formation of the company in 1882. One source states Coe Hill was not reached until 1889, but this appears to be an error.}} The first load of ore left the station on 2 June 1884,{{sfn|Walker|2013}} but when the samples reached [[Cleveland]] for analysis the results showed that the ore was too low grade to be useful for mining, leaving the company on the verge of bankruptcy.{{sfn|Bray}}\n\n===Further routes and branches===\n[[File:Central Ontario Railway in Bancroft.jpg|thumb|A Canadian Northern Railway (CNoR) passenger train heads south out of Bancroft station in 1910.]]\n\nFrom that point the company turned to servicing other mines and sawmills in the area and constructed a number of branch lines. As early as May 1891, the '''Ontario, Belmont & Northern Railway''' (OB&NR), a wholly owned subsidiary of the COR, received a charter to build a branch line to the iron mines in the Marmora area. Construction did not start for some time, and the 14.5&nbsp;km line from Marmora Junction near Belmar to the Cordova mines was finally completed in July 1896. Later that year the branch was renamed to become the '''Marmora Railway & Mining Company'''.\n\nStarting in 1899 the mainline was extended further north, not from the original terminus in Coe Hill which became a branch line, but by via a wye off the line south of Brinklow and running almost due north from that point, roughly following the route of the modern [[Ontario Highway 62]]. The 19.55 mile extension to Bancroft opened on 2 November 1900.{{sfn|Walker|2013}} Another subsidiary line, the '''Bessemer and Barry's Bay Railway''', was chartered in 1904 (although apparently formed in the late 1800s) to branch off the COR at L'Amable, just south of Bancroft, and run eastward to connect to Bessemer and the Child's Mine. Later, plans were made to use this branch as the basis for an extension all the way to the  [[Ottawa, Arnprior and Parry Sound Railway]], at that time the busiest railway in Canada,<ref>\"Track and Tower\" brochure, Friends of Algonquin Park</ref> meeting it at [[Barry's Bay, Ontario|Barry's Bay]]. However, the extension plans were never taken up and the B&BB remained a spur ending Child's Mine.\n\nA connection with the OA&PS, by this time reorganized to become part of the [[Canadian Atlantic Railway]] (CAR), remained desirable. A new route running from the Bancroft  terminus was selected, running almost due north to meet the CAR near [[Whitney, Ontario|Whitney]], just outside today's [[Algonquin Provincial Park]]. Construction on this link reached Maynooth on 7 November 1907, Lake St. Peter in 1909, and Wallace in 1911<ref name=bob>[http://www.railwaybob.com/Constituents/CNoRConstituents.htm \"Central Ontario Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217020851/http://www.railwaybob.com/Constituents/CNoRConstituents.htm |date=February 17, 2014 }}, Railway Bob</ref> - so-named for the line's surveyor and chief engineer.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}} By this time the logging era had reached its peak and traffic was dwindling on the COR, and further expansion was abandoned, leaving the end of the line a turnaround-wye next to Joseph Lavalley's farm in Wallace.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}}\n\n===Leasing, purchase and abandonment===\n[[File:Maynooth Station 1971.jpg|thumb|By the time this photo was taken in 1971, the COR north of Maynooth had been abandoned and the section north of Bancroft was little used. Maynooth station is already in shabby condition.]]\n\nIn 1910 the entire COR was leased by the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway]], which was itself purchased by the [[Canadian Northern Railway]] (CNoR) in 1911. The Canadian government took control of the CNoR in 1916, and folded its holdings into the forming [[Canadian National Railways]] (CNR) in 1918.<ref name=bob/> Under CN ownership, various sections were renamed as subdivisions; the line from Picton to Trenton became the '''Picton Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Picton.html \"C.N.Rys. Picton Subdivision\"]</ref> the mainline to Maynooth became the '''Maynooth Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Maynooth.html \"C.N.Rys. Maynooth Subdivision\"]</ref> while the various spurs became the '''Coe Hill Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Coe_Hill.html \"C.N.Rys. Coe Hill Subdivision\"]</ref> the '''Marmora Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Marmora.html \"C.N.Rys. Marmora Subdivision\"]</ref> and the '''Bessemer Subdivision'''.<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Bessemer.html \"C.N.Rys. Bessemer Subdivision\"]</ref>\n\nThe line was kept active by a series of small lumber mills that opened in the Lake McKenzie area. McConnell's Mill near the current intersection of McKenzie Lake Road and [[Ontario Highway 127]] was the first of these, and later taken over by the [[Rathburn Lumber|Rathbun Lumber Company]]. Judson Gunters opened a mill slightly to the north around 1918, which gives its name to maps to this day. The final mill in the area opened in 1943 when J.S.L. McRea moved his mill from Lake of Two Rivers in Algonquin to the area just north of Wallace. This mill operated until 1952.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}}\n\nWith the closing of the McRea mill and several other businesses in the area, traffic on the northern section of the line quickly dwindled. By 1955 all the business in Wallace had closed, and the COR ran a single train to the town every Wednesday to deliver mail. This section was abandoned in 1960, leaving the terminus at Lake St. Peter. On 22 April 1964 CNR applied to abandon the entire line from Wallace to Bird's Creek, just north of Bancroft where the COR met the Irondale (at today's \"Y\" Road). But only a smaller section, from Maynooth to Lake St. Peter was abandoned in 1965,{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}} along with most of the spurs. The remainder of the line was abandoned by CNR in 1984, and the rails lifted either that year or the next. Today only a 1.5&nbsp;km long section of the line remains, used by [[CN Rail]] as a siding to service the grain terminal at Trenton junction.\n\n===Conversion to rail-trail===\n[[File:Northern end of the Central Ontario Railway.JPG|thumb|Looking south from the northernmost \"navigable\" point of the COR, at the ghost town of Gunters.]]\n[[File:Maynooth Ontario railway station.jpg|thumb|Maynooth Station on the COR, about 2 km east of the town of Maynooth, Ontario. The station was the northernmost major station on the Central Ontario Railway.]]\n\nMost of the COR, including the original PECR route, has been converted to rail-trail use. After its abandonment the line has increasingly been turned to local authorities for maintenance.\n\nThe route of the original PECR was purchased by Prince Edward County in 1997 and is now known as the [http://www.ontariotrails.on.ca/trails-a-z/millennium-trail-1 Millennium Trail], running for 49&nbsp;km out of Picton and ending just outside Trenton.<ref>[http://www.pecounty.on.ca/government/eng_dev_works/pdf/MilleniumTrailMap.pdf Map of the Millennium Trail] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826023249/http://pecounty.on.ca/government/eng_dev_works/pdf/MilleniumTrailMap.pdf |date=2014-08-26 }}.</ref>\n\nThe 17&nbsp;km section between [[Ontario Highway 401|the 401]] at Trenton and Glen Ross had been re-used for roadways and other uses, as well as being in a built-up area. The unused sections in this area only started conversion to trail use in the 2000s, and several of these sections opened in 2011. Just north of Trenton this is known as the Jack Lange Memorial Trail, and from there, from just south of {{Not a typo|Glen Miller}} to Glen Ross, it becomes the Lower Trent Trail.<ref>[http://www.friendsofthetrail.ca \"Welcome to the Lower Trent Trail\"]</ref>\n\nThe largest section of the trail network is the {{convert|156|km|adj=on}} long four-season [https://web.archive.org/web/20140515175353/http://www.hastingscounty.com/discovering-hastings/hastings-heritage-trail.html Hastings Heritage Trail], stretching from Glen Ross all the way to [[Lake St. Peter Provincial Park]] outside Maynooth.<ref>[http://www.ontariotrailmaps.ca/5G.page Map of the Hastings Heritage Trail]</ref> This is the official end of the line, where it hits the border between [[Hastings County]] and [[South Algonquin]]. The trail remains in good repair, signed and used, north of this border to its current ending point near [[McKenzie Lake (Madawaska River)|McKenzie Lake]], at the intersection of McKenzie Lake Road and McKenzie North Road, marked on many maps as the village of Gunters.<ref>[https://maps.google.ca/maps?q=gunters+ontario \"Gunters, Ontario\"], as it appears in Google Maps.</ref>\n\nThe short remaining section from Gunters to Wallace is used for a variety of purposes, including section of McKenzie Lake Road, [[Hydro One]] lines providing local service, and in some areas simply abandoned and heavily overgrown. The ultimate terminus can be seen a few meters to the west of McKenzie Lake Road at the [[ghost town]] of Wallace.\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Central Ontario Railway map 1910.pdf|thumb|This map, from the COR's June 1910 passenger timetable, shows the route running all the way to Whitney. It actually ended near the \"Y\" in \"RAILWAY\", in Sabine County.]]\nThe original Prince Edward County Railway ran almost due west out of Picton towards the western shore of the Prince Edward County peninsula. It turned northwest at [[Wellington, Ontario|Wellington]] and then due north at [[Hillier, Ontario|Hillier]] before turning northwest again at Consecon to loop around the western end of the [[Bay of Quinte]] and then northeast for the short remaining distance to Trenton. There were ten stations on the line, Picton, Bloomfield at 4.22 miles, Hallowell 7.59 miles, Wellington 10.97 miles, Niles' Corner 14.90 miles, Hillier 16.55 miles, Consecon 21.32 miles, [[Weller's Bay]] 25.64 miles, Canal 27.02 miles and Trenton 30.60 miles.<ref>[http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/100-prince-edward-county-railway \"Prince Edward County Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002074301/http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/100-prince-edward-county-railway |date=October 2, 2013 }}</ref> This section of the line was abandoned in 1984 and the rails removed, but now the majority is used for a recreational trail. The original Picton Station is located on Main Street, and is occupied by C.F. Evans Lumber Company.\n\nFrom Trenton the line ran almost due north through Frankford, Glen Ross, Anson, Bonariaw, Marmora Station (just northeast of Marmora) and Deloror. Here it turned northeast toward Malone, and then east through Madoc to Eldorado. The line then turned north to run through Bannockburn, Millbridge Station and Gilmour, before turning west just south of Brinklow and running through Ormsby to its end just southwest of Coe Hill.\n\nThe Bancroft extension wyed off near Brinklow at Ormsby Junction, running north through Brinklow and detouring to the east en route to serve Detlor before reaching Bancroft. The next extension took it north from Bancroft to Maynooth Station (east of Maynooth). The original plans would have had it run roughly northeast along the route of [[Ontario Highway 62]] to [[Barry's Bay]], but instead took it northward along the route of [[Ontario Highway 127]] through [[Lake St. Peter Provincial Park]] before ultimately ending in the bush near McKenzie Lake.\n\nThere were two main spur lines. One split just south of Marmora at Belmar Station to run northwest to Cordova Mines, and the other split at Bessemer Junction near Detlor running east-northeast to Childs Mine.\n\nThe COR was joined by several other railways in the area. The [[Grand Junction Railway (Ontario)|Grand Junction Railway]] (GJR) ran between [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]] and Belleville and met the COR in a wye junction just outside the town of Anson, near [[Stirling, Ontario|Stirling]]. A branch of the GJR, the Belleville and North Hastings Railway (B&NH), later met the COR about 1&nbsp;km west of Eldorado. The [[Bay of Quinte Railway]] was extended to meet the COR just north of Eldorado at Bannockburn, reaching this point in 1902.<ref>[http://vishwawalking.ca/hastings-heritage-trail/hast-hertge-trl-of-2-lkes.html \"Trail of Two Lakes, Belleville and North Hastings Line\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/93-belleville-north-hastings \"Belleville and North Hastings Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002041723/http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/93-belleville-north-hastings |date=October 2, 2013 }}</ref> The final connection was to the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway|Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa]] which met the COR just north of Bancroft in 1910, meeting it at what it today known as \"Y\" Road, named for the wye intersection.\n\nMain stations on the line included Picton, Bloomfield, Wellington, Trenton, Frankford, Marmora, Coe Hill, Bancroft and Maynooth. Several stations have survived; the original Picton station was moved and became a private home, while the second station remains in use as a lumberyard. Hallowell was moved to Stanley Street in Bloomfield as a children's playhouse, Bloomfield moved to West Lake as a summer residence, Consecon is abandoned in place, Frankford moved to Stockdale as a restaurant, Marmora and Coe Hill both moved to a park to become information centres, Bancroft's station remains in place and is now a museum, Maynooth was abandoned in place (see image at top) and Lake St. Peter was moved to an unknown location.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |first=Matt |last=Bray |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/ritchie_samuel_j_13E.html |title=Ritchie, Samuel J. |website=[[Dictionary of Canadian Biography]] |volume=XIII |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |first=Ron |last=Brown |url=http://countryroadshastings.ca/current-issue-s2.php?command=viewArticle&ID=7&currentFeed=3 |title=The ghost rail lines of Hastings County |website=Country Roads |date=17 June 2011 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624023930/http://countryroadshastings.ca/current-issue-s2.php?command=viewArticle&ID=7&currentFeed=3 |archivedate=24 June 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |first=Jim |last=Walker |url=http://blog.harveyhistoricalsociety.ca/canadian-railways/ |title=Canadian Railways |website=Harvey Historical Society |date=1 February 2013 |ref=harv |access-date=4 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000358/http://blog.harveyhistoricalsociety.ca/canadian-railways/ |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite book |last=Lyons |first=Bob |title=Whitney: Island in the Shield |publisher=Bancroft Times |year=1986 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/castelmar/105663683/ This image] is a marked up version of the map in the 1910 timetable, highlighting nearby railways. The COR is in green, with the branch lines to Marmora, Coe Hill (Wollaston) and Child's Mine (Mayo). The route is shown complete to Whitney at the northern edge of the map, but actually ends at McKenzie Lake, the northernmost lake just to the right of the route, in the southeast corner of Sabine County. The railway ended at about the point of the \"y\" in the word \"Railway\". The original planned terminus in Barry's Bay is just off the upper right corner of the map. The blue line is the [[Bay of Quinte Railway]] to Deseronto.\n\n{{Canada class 2}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct Ontario railways]]\n[[Category:Predecessors of the Canadian Northern Railway]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1879]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1910]]\n[[Category:1910 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1910 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail | gauge={{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n|railroad_name= Central Ontario Railway\n|marks=COR\n|image=COR first train arrival.jpg\n|image_caption=A crowd gathers on the Central Ontario Railway platform in Bancroft to await the arrival of the first train on 2 November 1900.\n|logo_size=125\n|logo_filename=\n|system_map=\n|map_size=\n|map_caption= \n|old_gauge=\n|locale=[[Ontario]], Canada\n|start_year= 1879\n|end_year=1984\n|hq_city=\n|length={{convert|50.9|miles}}\n|predecessor_line  = Prince Edward County Railway\n|successor_line    = Canadian Northern Railway/ CN\n}}\n\nThe '''Central Ontario Railway''' ('''COR''') was a former [[railway]] that ran north from [[Trenton, Ontario]] to service a number of towns, mines and sawmills. The railway originally formed as the '''Prince Edward County Railway''' in 1879, running between [[Picton, Ontario|Picton]] and Trenton, where it connected with the [[Grand Trunk Railway]] that ran between [[Montreal]] and [[Toronto]]. After being purchased by a group of investors and receiving a new charter to build northward, the railway renamed as the COR in 1882 and the company started building towards the gold fields at [[Madoc, Ontario|Eldorado]] and newly discovered iron fields in Coe Hill.\n\nOn reaching Coe Hill in 1884, the mine was found to have low grade ore, nearly bankrupting the company. Expansion continued to other mining areas around [[Bancroft, Ontario|Bancroft]], along with two wholly owned subsidiary lines, the '''Ontario, Belmont and Northern Railway''', later known as the '''Marmora Railway''', and the '''Bessemer and Barry's Bay Railway'''. The later was supposed to connect to the [[Ottawa, Arnprior and Parry Sound Railway]] (OA&PS) at [[Barry's Bay, Ontario|Barry's Bay]], but these plans were shelved. A new route to the OA&PS was selected to [[Whitney, Ontario|Whitney]], just outside [[Algonquin Provincial Park]]. Construction on this final portion reached [[Maynooth, Ontario|Maynooth]] in 1907 but was never completed, and the line ultimately ended in the now abandoned town of Wallace, about 25 kilometres south of Whitney.\n\nThe COR was taken over by [[William Mackenzie (railway entrepreneur)|Mackenzie]] and [[Donald Mann|Mann]] in 1910, along with the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway]] which was connected to the COR north of Bancroft in July 1910. Both lines were then merged into their [[Canadian Northern Railway]] (CNoR) in 1911. After CNoR was nationalized 1918, the lines became part of the [[Canadian National Railways]] (CN) system in 1923. CN operated the COR as the '''Maynooth Subdivision'''. Sections of the line north of Maynooth were lifted in 1965, and the entire rest of the line in 1985. All of the side branches had been abandoned much earlier, typically when the ore deposits dried up.\n\nMuch of the route of the COR has been re-purposed as a multi-use recreational [[rail trail]], which has a variety of names depending on its location, with the '''Hastings Heritage Trail''' being a prominent part.\n\n==History==\n\n===Prince Edward County Railway===\n[[Prince Edward County, Ontario|Prince Edward County]] is a large peninsula on eastern [[Lake Ontario]]. It is roughly triangular in shape with its apex pointed to the east, and its connection to the mainland at the northwestern corner. It was first settled starting in 1784 by [[Loyalist (American Revolution)|Loyalists]] after the [[American Revolutionary War]], and depended largely on fishing and barley in its early days.\n\nThe [[Grand Trunk Railway]] (GTR) reached [[Belleville, Ontario|Belleville]] on its way to Toronto in 1855, opening new markets to the County. Local businessmen began considering a railway to collect produce from across the peninsula and connecting with the GTR at Trenton, on the north side of the land bridge with the mainland.{{sfn|Brown|2011}} The Prince Edward County Railway company (PECR) was formed in 1873{{efn|Sources disagree on the date, some suggesting that it was formed in 1879 and opened in 1880, while others give 1873 as the formation and 1879 as the opening date.}} and began construction due west out of Picton towards the western shore of the peninsula, then turning northward for Trenton. Due to financial constraints, the line finally completed in 1879 and opened for service in October.{{sfn|Brown|2011}} In 1976 a large branch was wyed off west of Picton to serve large quarries north of town, near Elmbrook.\n\n===Expansion to Coe Hill===\nThe opening of [[Central Ontario]] during the 19th Century was driven primarily by the discovery of a number of mineral deposits, notably gold and iron ore. As mines grew, principally in the area of [[Marmora, Ontario|Marmora]] and [[Madoc, Ontario|Madoc]], a race formed between a series of railways companies who wanted to serve these markets. Among the many claimants were the [[Victoria Railway]] (VicR) that ran through [[Lindsay, Ontario|Lindsay]], a combined rail and water route by the [[Cobourg and Peterborough Railway]] (C&P), and a potential extension of the [[Toronto and Nipissing Railway]]. None of these were well placed though, as they ran towards Toronto instead of east to the major markets and shipping routes. The only line that appeared to be well positioned was a proposed branch of the [[Grand Junction Railway (Ontario)|Grand Junction Railway]] (GJR) out of Belleville. Since the new mining areas were directly north of both Trenton and Belleville, the PERC was also in an ideal location as a starting point.\n\nWilliam Coe of [[Madoc, Ontario|Madoc]] found [[iron ore]] deposits outside Brinklow and began looking for ways to commercialize the find. He contacted [[George William McMullen]], a railway promoter in [[Chicago]] who had been born and raised in Picton. McMullen started looking for partners, and found [[Samuel Ritchey]], a businessman from [[Ohio]] who was looking for new ventures. Rickey, McMullen and McMullen's brother J.B. bought the PECR in 1880 to serve as the basis for a rapid expansion. In 1881 the group purchased 70,000 acres of land for the mines, and transferred the deeds to the company.{{sfn|Bray}} The group then petitioned the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|Ontario Legislature]] for the rights to rename the company and start construction northward, which was granted on 10 March 1882.{{sfn|Walker|2013}} The land deeds were transferred to the newly formed Coe Hill Mining Company, and the railway was renamed the Central Ontario Railway.{{sfn|Bray}}\n\nThe route was selected to take the line through several other mining areas, including Marmora, Deloro and Malone, before reaching Eldorado. The line reached Marmora in 1883 and the newly formed [[Wollaston, Ontario|Coe Hill]] in 1884.{{efn|Most sources agree this took place in 1884, either directly or by saying \"two years later\" after formation of the company in 1882. One source states Coe Hill was not reached until 1889, but this appears to be an error.}} The first load of ore left the station on 2 June 1884,{{sfn|Walker|2013}} but when the samples reached [[Cleveland]] for analysis the results showed that the ore was too low grade to be useful for mining, leaving the company on the verge of bankruptcy.{{sfn|Bray}}\n\n===Further routes and branches===\n[[File:Central Ontario Railway in Bancroft.jpg|thumb|A Canadian Northern Railway (CNoR) passenger train heads south out of Bancroft station in 1910.]]\n\nFrom that point the company turned to servicing other mines and sawmills in the area and constructed a number of branch lines. As early as May 1891, the '''Ontario, Belmont & Northern Railway''' (OB&NR), a wholly owned subsidiary of the COR, received a charter to build a branch line to the iron mines in the Marmora area. Construction did not start for some time, and the 14.5&nbsp;km line from Marmora Junction near Belmar to the Cordova mines was finally completed in July 1896. Later that year the branch was renamed to become the '''Marmora Railway & Mining Company'''.\n\nStarting in 1899 the mainline was extended further north, not from the original terminus in Coe Hill which became a branch line, but by via a wye off the line south of Brinklow and running almost due north from that point, roughly following the route of the modern [[Ontario Highway 62]]. The 19.55 mile extension to Bancroft opened on 2 November 1900.{{sfn|Walker|2013}} Another subsidiary line, the '''Bessemer and Barry's Bay Railway''', was chartered in 1904 (although apparently formed in the late 1800s) to branch off the COR at L'Amable, just south of Bancroft, and run eastward to connect to Bessemer and the Child's Mine. Later, plans were made to use this branch as the basis for an extension all the way to the  [[Ottawa, Arnprior and Parry Sound Railway]], at that time the busiest railway in Canada,<ref>\"Track and Tower\" brochure, Friends of Algonquin Park</ref> meeting it at [[Barry's Bay, Ontario|Barry's Bay]]. However, the extension plans were never taken up and the B&BB remained a spur ending Child's Mine.\n\nA connection with the OA&PS, by this time reorganized to become part of the [[Canadian Atlantic Railway]] (CAR), remained desirable. A new route running from the Bancroft  terminus was selected, running almost due north to meet the CAR near [[Whitney, Ontario|Whitney]], just outside today's [[Algonquin Provincial Park]]. Construction on this link reached Maynooth on 7 November 1907, Lake St. Peter in 1909, and Wallace in 1911<ref name=bob>[http://www.railwaybob.com/Constituents/CNoRConstituents.htm \"Central Ontario Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217020851/http://www.railwaybob.com/Constituents/CNoRConstituents.htm |date=February 17, 2014 }}, Railway Bob</ref> - so-named for the line's surveyor and chief engineer.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}} By this time the logging era had reached its peak and traffic was dwindling on the COR, and further expansion was abandoned, leaving the end of the line a turnaround-wye next to Joseph Lavalley's farm in Wallace.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}}\n\n===Leasing, purchase and abandonment===\n[[File:Maynooth Station 1971.jpg|thumb|By the time this photo was taken in 1971, the COR north of Maynooth had been abandoned and the section north of Bancroft was little used. Maynooth station is already in shabby condition.]]\n\nIn 1910 the entire COR was leased by the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway]], which was itself purchased by the [[Canadian Northern Railway]] (CNoR) in 1911. The Canadian government took control of the CNoR in 1916, and folded its holdings into the forming [[Canadian National Railways]] (CNR) in 1918.<ref name=bob/> Under CN ownership, various sections were renamed as subdivisions; the line from Picton to Trenton became the '''Picton Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Picton.html \"C.N.Rys. Picton Subdivision\"]</ref> the mainline to Maynooth became the '''Maynooth Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Maynooth.html \"C.N.Rys. Maynooth Subdivision\"]</ref> while the various spurs became the '''Coe Hill Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Coe_Hill.html \"C.N.Rys. Coe Hill Subdivision\"]</ref> the '''Marmora Subdivision''',<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Marmora.html \"C.N.Rys. Marmora Subdivision\"]</ref> and the '''Bessemer Subdivision'''.<ref>[http://www.cnr-in-ontario.com/Subdivisions/Bessemer.html \"C.N.Rys. Bessemer Subdivision\"]</ref>\n\nThe line was kept active by a series of small lumber mills that opened in the Lake McKenzie area. McConnell's Mill near the current intersection of McKenzie Lake Road and [[Ontario Highway 127]] was the first of these, and later taken over by the [[Rathburn Lumber|Rathbun Lumber Company]]. Judson Gunters opened a mill slightly to the north around 1918, which gives its name to maps to this day. The final mill in the area opened in 1943 when J.S.L. McRea moved his mill from Lake of Two Rivers in Algonquin to the area just north of Wallace. This mill operated until 1952.{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}}\n\nWith the closing of the McRea mill and several other businesses in the area, traffic on the northern section of the line quickly dwindled. By 1955 all the business in Wallace had closed, and the COR ran a single train to the town every Wednesday to deliver mail. This section was abandoned in 1960, leaving the terminus at Lake St. Peter. On 22 April 1964 CNR applied to abandon the entire line from Wallace to Bird's Creek, just north of Bancroft where the COR met the Irondale (at today's \"Y\" Road). But only a smaller section, from Maynooth to Lake St. Peter was abandoned in 1965,{{sfn|Lyons|1986|loc=Chapter 7}} along with most of the spurs. The remainder of the line was abandoned by CNR in 1984, and the rails lifted either that year or the next. Today only a 1.5&nbsp;km long section of the line remains, used by [[CN Rail]] as a siding to service the grain terminal at Trenton junction.\n\n===Conversion to rail-trail===\n[[File:Northern end of the Central Ontario Railway.JPG|thumb|Looking south from the northernmost \"navigable\" point of the COR, at the ghost town of Gunters.]]\n[[File:Maynooth Ontario railway station.jpg|thumb|Maynooth Station on the COR, about 2 km east of the town of Maynooth, Ontario. The station was the northernmost major station on the Central Ontario Railway.]]\n\nMost of the COR, including the original PECR route, has been converted to rail-trail use. After its abandonment the line has increasingly been turned to local authorities for maintenance.\n\nThe route of the original PECR was purchased by Prince Edward County in 1997 and is now known as the [http://www.ontariotrails.on.ca/trails-a-z/millennium-trail-1 Millennium Trail], running for 49&nbsp;km out of Picton and ending just outside Trenton.<ref>[http://www.pecounty.on.ca/government/eng_dev_works/pdf/MilleniumTrailMap.pdf Map of the Millennium Trail] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826023249/http://pecounty.on.ca/government/eng_dev_works/pdf/MilleniumTrailMap.pdf |date=2014-08-26 }}.</ref>\n\nThe 17&nbsp;km section between [[Ontario Highway 401|the 401]] at Trenton and Glen Ross had been re-used for roadways and other uses, as well as being in a built-up area. The unused sections in this area only started conversion to trail use in the 2000s, and several of these sections opened in 2011. Just north of Trenton this is known as the Jack Lange Memorial Trail, and from there, from just south of {{Not a typo|Glen Miller}} to Glen Ross, it becomes the Lower Trent Trail.<ref>[http://www.friendsofthetrail.ca \"Welcome to the Lower Trent Trail\"]</ref>\n\nThe largest section of the trail network is the 156&nbsp;km long four-season [https://web.archive.org/web/20140515175353/http://www.hastingscounty.com/discovering-hastings/hastings-heritage-trail.html Hastings Heritage Trail], stretching from Glen Ross all the way to [[Lake St. Peter Provincial Park]] outside Maynooth.<ref>[http://www.ontariotrailmaps.ca/5G.page Map of the Hastings Heritage Trail]</ref> This is the official end of the line, where it hits the border between [[Hastings County]] and [[South Algonquin]]. The trail remains in good repair, signed and used, north of this border to its current ending point near [[McKenzie Lake (Moore Creek)|McKenzie Lake]], at the intersection of McKenzie Lake Road and McKenzie Lake North, marked on many maps as the village of Gunters.<ref>[https://maps.google.ca/maps?q=gunters+ontario \"Gunters, Ontario\"], as it appears in Google Maps.</ref>\n\nThe short remaining section from Gunters to Wallace is used for a variety of purposes, including section of McKenzie Lake Road, [[Hydro One]] lines providing local service, and in some areas simply abandoned and heavily overgrown. The ultimate terminus can be seen a few meters to the west of McKenzie Lake Road at the [[ghost town]] of Wallace.\n\n==Route==\n[[File:Central Ontario Railway map 1910.pdf|thumb|This map, from the COR's June 1910 passenger timetable, shows the route running all the way to Whitney. It actually ended near the \"Y\" in \"RAILWAY\", in Sabine County.]]\nThe original Prince Edward County Railway ran almost due west out of Picton towards the western shore of the Prince Edward County peninsula. It turned northwest at [[Wellington, Ontario|Wellington]] and then due north at [[Hillier, Ontario|Hillier]] before turning northwest again at Consecon to loop around the western end of the [[Bay of Quinte]] and then northeast for the short remaining distance to Trenton. There were ten stations on the line, Picton, Bloomfield at 4.22 miles, Hallowell 7.59 miles, Wellington 10.97 miles, Niles' Corner 14.90 miles, Hillier 16.55 miles, Consecon 21.32 miles, [[Weller's Bay]] 25.64 miles, Canal 27.02 miles and Trenton 30.60 miles.<ref>[http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/100-prince-edward-county-railway \"Prince Edward County Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002074301/http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/100-prince-edward-county-railway |date=October 2, 2013 }}</ref> This section of the line was abandoned in 1984 and the rails removed, but now the majority is used for a recreational trail. The original Picton Station is located on Main Street, and is occupied by C.F. Evans Lumber Company.\n\nFrom Trenton the line ran almost due north through Frankford, Glen Ross, Anson, Bonariaw, Marmora Station (just northeast of Marmora) and Deloror. Here it turned northeast toward Malone, and then east through Madoc to Eldorado. The line then turned north to run through Bannockburn, Millbridge Station and Gilmour, before turning west just south of Brinklow and running through Ormsby to its end just southwest of Coe Hill.\n\nThe Bancroft extension wyed off near Brinklow at Ormsby Junction, running north through Brinklow and detouring to the east en route to serve Detlor before reaching Bancroft. The next extension took it north from Bancroft to Maynooth Station (east of Maynooth). The original plans would have had it run roughly northeast along the route of [[Ontario Highway 62]] to [[Barry's Bay]], but instead took it northward along the route of [[Ontario Highway 127]] through [[Lake St. Peter Provincial Park]] before ultimately ending in the bush near McKenzie Lake.\n\nThere were two main spur lines. One split just south of Marmora at Belmar Station to run northwest to Cordova Mines, and the other split at Bessemer Junction near Detlor running east-northeast to Childs Mine.\n\nThe COR was joined by several other railways in the area. The [[Grand Junction Railway (Ontario)|Grand Junction Railway]] (GJR) ran between [[Peterborough, Ontario|Peterborough]] and Belleville and met the COR in a wye junction just outside the town of Anson, near [[Stirling, Ontario|Stirling]]. A branch of the GJR, the Belleville and North Hastings Railway (B&NH), later met the COR about 1&nbsp;km west of Eldorado. The [[Bay of Quinte Railway]] was extended to meet the COR just north of Eldorado at Bannockburn, reaching this point in 1902.<ref>[http://vishwawalking.ca/hastings-heritage-trail/hast-hertge-trl-of-2-lkes.html \"Trail of Two Lakes, Belleville and North Hastings Line\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/93-belleville-north-hastings \"Belleville and North Hastings Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002041723/http://www.bellevillemodelrailroad.org/index.php/local-history/93-belleville-north-hastings |date=October 2, 2013 }}</ref> The final connection was to the [[Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa Railway|Irondale, Bancroft and Ottawa]] which met the COR just north of Bancroft in 1910, meeting it at what it today known as \"Y\" Road, named for the wye intersection.\n\nMain stations on the line included Picton, Bloomfield, Wellington, Trenton, Frankford, Marmora, Coe Hill, Bancroft and Maynooth. Several stations have survived; the original Picton station was moved and became a private home, while the second station remains in use as a lumberyard. Hallowell was moved to Stanley Street in Bloomfield as a children's playhouse, Bloomfield moved to West Lake as a summer residence, Consecon is abandoned in place, Frankford moved to Stockdale as a restaurant, Marmora and Coe Hill both moved to a park to become information centres, Bancroft's station remains in place and is now a museum, Maynooth was abandoned in place (see image at top) and Lake St. Peter was moved to an unknown location.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |first=Matt |last=Bray |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/ritchie_samuel_j_13E.html |title=Ritchie, Samuel J. |website=[[Dictionary of Canadian Biography]] |volume=XIII |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |first=Ron |last=Brown |url=http://countryroadshastings.ca/current-issue-s2.php?command=viewArticle&ID=7&currentFeed=3 |title=The ghost rail lines of Hastings County |website=Country Roads |date=17 June 2011 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624023930/http://countryroadshastings.ca/current-issue-s2.php?command=viewArticle&ID=7&currentFeed=3 |archivedate=24 June 2013 }}\n* {{cite web |first=Jim |last=Walker |url=http://blog.harveyhistoricalsociety.ca/canadian-railways/ |title=Canadian Railways |website=Harvey Historical Society |date=1 February 2013 |ref=harv |access-date=4 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000358/http://blog.harveyhistoricalsociety.ca/canadian-railways/ |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite book |last=Lyons |first=Bob |title=Whitney: Island in the Shield |publisher=Bancroft Times |year=1986 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/castelmar/105663683/ This image] is a marked up version of the map in the 1910 timetable, highlighting nearby railways. The COR is in green, with the branch lines to Marmora, Coe Hill (Wollaston) and Child's Mine (Mayo). The route is shown complete to Whitney at the northern edge of the map, but actually ends at McKenzie Lake, the northernmost lake just to the right of the route, in the southeast corner of Sabine County. The railway ended at about the point of the \"y\" in the word \"Railway\". The original planned terminus in Barry's Bay is just off the upper right corner of the map. The blue line is the [[Bay of Quinte Railway]] to Deseronto.\n\n{{Canada class 2}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct Ontario railways]]\n[[Category:Predecessors of the Canadian Northern Railway]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1879]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1910]]\n[[Category:1910 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1910 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Qui1che", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConversion to rail-trail:Updated link, corrected road name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Ontario_Railway"}
